                <div type="typology">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">West (Maghreb) › Tunisia › Southwestern Tunisia</p>
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Bedouin-type dialect with numerous elements from sedentary
              dialects</p>
                </div>
                <div type="general">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Tozeur as the capital of the Tozeur Governorate is located in
              South-western Tunisia. The oasis which is well known for its vast
              date palm groves and its typical clay brick architecture is
              situated north of the Chott el-Djerid. For centuries, the town was
              a main hub for caravans crossing the Sahara.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="researchHistory">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">The dialect spoken in Tozeur is a transitional Bedouin-type
              dialect that shows features of both the Hilal- and Sulaym-type
              dialects, but also considerable influence of sedentary dialects.
              Hitherto little research has been done on the dialect of Tozeur.
              Information on phonology, morphology, and syntax is provided by
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:SR2MYQQU">Saada (1984)</rs>; a corpus
              of mainly ethnographic texts was published by the same author in
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:GX56I4BF">(1981)</rs>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="dictionaries">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:SR2MYQQU">Saada (1984)</rs> also
              contains a 30-page glossary.</p>
                </div>
